# Everything here is excluded from the build context shipped to the
# daemon. Bind mounts in compose IGNORE this file at RUNTIME — heavy
# directories like ./tracks still show up in the container via the
# volume mounts. The point of this list is to keep ``docker build``
# fast: a ~12 GB project shouldn't transfer 12 GB to the daemon for
# each rebuild.

# --- VCS + editor ---
.git/
.github/
.gitignore
.gitattributes
.vscode/
.idea/
*.swp
*.swo
.DS_Store

# --- Python build artifacts ---
# Leading ``**/`` matches at any depth — without it, ``__pycache__/``
# would only catch ``./__pycache__/`` at the context root and miss
# ``./web/backend/__pycache__/`` etc. Same story for the patterns
# below.
**/__pycache__
**/*.pyc
**/*.pyo
**/.pytest_cache
**/.mypy_cache
**/.ruff_cache
**/*.egg-info
**/build
**/dist

# --- Python virtualenvs (host's is wrong-arch anyway) ---
.venv/
venv/
env/

# --- Node ---
# Recursive ``**/`` matters MORE here — the actual node_modules sits at
# web/frontend/node_modules (585 MB on this machine), and a non-recursive
# ``node_modules/`` would only have caught a non-existent root-level
# one. Same for the Next.js build dirs.
**/node_modules
**/.next
**/.next-e2e
**/out
**/playwright-report
**/playwright/.cache
**/test-results

# --- HEAVY runtime data — bind-mounted, never baked ---
# These are the catalog, generated mixes, and AI artwork. On a real
# laptop they add up to gigs. The bind mount in compose provides
# them at /app/{tracks,output,artwork} at runtime.
tracks/
output/
artwork/

# Agent memory + session DB stay on the host so they persist across
# rebuilds (the bind mount surfaces them inside the container).
agent/memory.json
agent/memory*.json

# --- Secrets ---
# .env IS read by compose's ``env_file`` directive — but must NOT be
# baked into the image (it would leak via ``docker history``).
.env
.env.*
!.env.example

# --- Databases ---
*.db
*.sqlite
*.sqlite3

# --- Logs / scratch ---
*.log
logs/
.routines/
.claude/

# --- Docker self ---
Dockerfile
docker-compose*.yml
docker/
